sublevels.theory:
Design patterns are reusable solutions to common programming problems.

**Singleton:** only one instance:
```java
class Database {
    private static Database instance;
    private Database() {}
    public static Database getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) instance = new Database();
        return instance;
    }
}
```

**Factory:** create objects without specifying exact class:
```java
interface Shape { void draw(); }
class ShapeFactory {
    public static Shape create(String type) {
        return switch (type) {
            case "circle" -> new Circle();
            default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException(type);
        };
    }
}
```

**Observer:** notify subscribers of state changes.

**Enum Singleton (thread-safe):**
```java
enum Singleton { INSTANCE; ... }
```

**Abstract Factory:** create families of related objects.

**Proxy pattern:** controls access to an object.

**Command pattern:**
```java
interface Command { void execute(); }
class LightOn implements Command {
    Light light;
    public void execute() { light.on(); }
}
```

**Iterator pattern:** `java.util.Iterator` — sequential access without exposing underlying structure.

**Composite pattern:** tree of objects treated uniformly (e.g., UI component hierarchy).
